            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the Massachusetts income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool focuses on
                <strong>Massachusetts state income tax</strong>. It does not
                calculate your federal income tax, FICA (Social Security and
                Medicare), or local city taxes. Those will further reduce your
                actual take‑home pay.
              </p>
              <p>
                Massachusetts currently uses a <strong>flat tax rate</strong> on
                most taxable income. That means the same percentage applies to
                your entire Massachusetts taxable income, unlike progressive
                systems with multiple brackets.
              </p>

              <h3>Step‑by‑step calculation</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Start with annual gross income</strong> (wages,
                  salary, bonuses, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtract <strong>pre‑tax deductions</strong> that reduce
                  Massachusetts taxable income (e.g., traditional 401(k), some
                  retirement contributions).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtract your estimated
                  <strong>Massachusetts deductions</strong> (student loan
                  interest, certain retirement contributions, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtract the
                  <strong>Massachusetts personal exemption</strong> based on
                  filing status.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtract <strong>dependent exemptions</strong> based on the
                  number of dependents.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you are a
                  <strong>nonresident or part‑year resident</strong>, multiply
                  by your
                  <strong>Massachusetts‑source income percentage</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply the <strong>flat Massachusetts tax rate</strong> to the
                  resulting taxable income.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">General formula (simplified)</p>
                <p>
                  <code>
                    MA taxable income = (Gross income − pre‑tax deductions − MA
                    deductions − personal exemption − dependent exemptions) ×
                    MA‑source %
                  </code>
                </p>
                <p>
                  <code> MA tax = MA taxable income × flat MA tax rate </code>
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Assumptions and simplifications</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Uses a single <strong>flat Massachusetts tax rate</strong> for
                  most income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Approximates
                  <strong>personal and dependent exemptions</strong> by filing
                  status and number of dependents.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Treats all income as taxed at the standard rate (special
                  capital‑gains rates are not modeled separately).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not include every possible
                  <strong>credit or special deduction</strong> (e.g., earned
                  income credit, certain refundable credits).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Using the Massachusetts income tax calculator effectively</h2>
              <h3>1. Choose the right filing status</h3>
              <p>
                Your filing status affects your exemption amount and sometimes
                eligibility for credits:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Single</strong> – Unmarried, not a dependent, and not
                  head of household.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Married filing jointly</strong> – Married couple
                  filing one combined return.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Married filing separately</strong> – Each spouse files
                  their own MA return.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Head of household</strong> – Unmarried with a
                  qualifying dependent and meeting support tests.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Estimate pre‑tax and Massachusetts‑specific deductions</h3>
              <p>For a more realistic estimate, include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pre‑tax deductions</strong>: traditional 401(k),
                  403(b), some retirement plans, HSA contributions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>MA deductions</strong>: certain student loan interest,
                  some retirement contributions, and other adjustments allowed
                  by Massachusetts law.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Residents vs. nonresidents</h3>
              <p>If you lived or worked in multiple states:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Residents</strong> are generally taxed on income from
                  all sources.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Nonresidents</strong> are taxed only on
                  <strong>Massachusetts‑source income</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Part‑year residents</strong> are taxed on all income
                  while a resident, plus MA‑source income while a nonresident.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use the
                <strong>“Nonresident / part‑year resident”</strong> checkbox and
                slider to approximate the share of your income taxable by
                Massachusetts.
              </p>

